---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import WorkflowSteps from "../components/WorkflowSteps.astro";

const description = "See how AntennaBench plans, conducts, records, and reports a repeatable WSPR antenna comparison without hiding uncertainty.";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How AntennaBench works"
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/how-it-works/"
>
  <section class="page-hero section-pad">
    <div class="shell narrow-shell">
      <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
      <h1>A guided WSPR experiment, not a one-number verdict</h1>
      <p>
        AntennaBench keeps the question, plan, operator actions, observations, and
        corrections separate. The report can then say what the run describes—and where
        the evidence stops.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-pad detail-workflow" aria-labelledby="overview-title">
    <div class="shell">
      <h2 id="overview-title" class="visually-hidden">Workflow overview</h2>
      <WorkflowSteps />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-pad process-section" aria-labelledby="before-title">
    <div class="shell process-grid">
      <div class="process-label"><span>Before</span><strong>Define the experiment</strong></div>
      <div class="process-copy">
        <h2 id="before-title">Start with what you want to learn</h2>
        <p>
          Choose a supported question: compare the whole station, ask where you are heard
          better, ask what you can hear better, or profile one antenna. Then enter the
          station, antennas, band, direction, and complete repetition count.
        </p>
        <p>
          The normalized review shows the directed counterbalanced order, cycle count,
          antenna-versus-direction changes, and required WSPR cycle time. It also states
          what the run cannot prove before any evidence is collected.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-pad process-section alt-process" aria-labelledby="during-title">
    <div class="shell process-grid">
      <div class="process-label"><span>During</span><strong>Record what happened</strong></div>
      <div class="process-copy">
        <h2 id="during-title">Switch, confirm, and follow the actual cadence</h2>
        <p>
          The app presents one current instruction at a time. After the physical antenna
          change, the operator presses the named ready action. AntennaBench then chooses
          the next eligible even-minute WSPR cycle.
        </p>
        <p>
          Missed or bad cycles, notes, corrections, interruptions, and optional controller
          failures remain explicit. Earlier evidence is retained instead of silently
          rewritten to match the plan.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-pad process-section" aria-labelledby="evidence-title">
    <div class="shell process-grid">
      <div class="process-label"><span>Evidence</span><strong>Keep sources distinct</strong></div>
      <div class="process-copy">
        <h2 id="evidence-title">Public spots, local decodes, imports, and operator facts</h2>
        <p>
          WSPR.live public spots can be gathered on a best-effort basis. Local WSJT-X
          decodes, bounded WSPR or Reverse Beacon Network imports, and operator facts keep
          their own provenance. A network gap does not erase evidence already safe on disk.
        </p>
        <aside class="explain-card">
          <strong>A missing decode is not zero signal.</strong>
          <p>Unmatched paths remain reach evidence; they are never inserted into paired SNR calculations as zeros.</p>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-pad process-section alt-process" aria-labelledby="reporting-title">
    <div class="shell process-grid">
      <div class="process-label"><span>After</span><strong>Read the evidence</strong></div>
      <div class="process-copy">
        <h2 id="reporting-title">Compare like with like, then inspect the limitations</h2>
        <p>
          The report can show zero-centered same-path differences, reach seen on only one
          comparison side, coverage and imbalance, switching-order context, and available
          distance, direction, or solar context. Comparisons stay separate by direction,
          band, mode, observation kind, and source.
        </p>
        <p>
          “Insufficient data” is a useful outcome. AntennaBench provides descriptive
          evidence today; it does not select a winner or claim a result generalizes beyond
          the recorded session.
        </p>
        <a class="button button-primary" href="/sample-report/">Read the canonical report</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="record-section" aria-labelledby="record-title">
    <div class="shell record-grid">
      <img src="/mark.svg" width="112" height="112" alt="" />
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Local-first by design</p>
        <h2 id="record-title">Your session bundle remains the durable record</h2>
        <p>
          The report is deterministic output that can be regenerated. Creating, conducting,
          reviewing, and exporting a session does not depend on this website or any account.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
